{"title_page": "Steve Casey", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{Infobox professional wrestler\n|name        = Steve Casey\n|names       =Steve Casey\n|image       = Steve 'The Crusher' Casey.jpg\n|caption    = Bronze statue of 'The Crusher' in Sneem\n|height      = {{height|foot=6|inch=4}}\n|weight      = {{convert|238|lb|kg|abbr=on}}\n|birth_date  = 4 December 1908\n|birth_place = [[Sneem]], [[History of Ireland (1801\u20131923)|Ireland]]\n|death_date  = 10 January 1987 (aged 78)\n|death_place =\n|birth_name = Stephen Casey\n|trainer     = Mike Casey\n|debut       = 3 March 1936\n|retired     = 1947\n}}\n\n'''Stephen Casey''' (4 December 1908 \u2013 10 January 1987) was an [[Ireland|Irish]] [[Rowing (sport)|sport rower]] and world champion [[Professional wrestling|professional wrestler]]. He was the second Irish wrestler, after [[Danno O'Mahoney]], to become a world champion.\n\n== Rowing ==\nCasey was the eldest of seven sons and three daughters of Mike Casey, a bare-knuckle boxer, and Brigid Sullivan. Steve Casey rowed in the Sneem senior crew with his father and the O'Connor Brothers. The Sneem/Casey Team won the Tug-O-War Munster Championship in 1932. Casey went on to win the Salter Challenge Cup with his brothers during 1930 to 1933. In 1936, he became the All-England Rowing Champion with his brothers Paddy, Tom and Mick. In the same year, the Caseys qualified for [[1936 Summer Olympics|the Olympics]] in [[Rowing at the 1936 Summer Olympics|rowing]] but were disqualified for Steve and Paddy being professional wrestlers because Steve had wrestled two professional matches before the Olympics.\n\n== Professional wrestling ==\nIn 1935, Steve and his brother Paddy Casey joined the British Amateur Wrestling Team. Steve Casey debuted as a professional wrestler on 3 March 1936 by beating the Irish Canadian Heavyweight Champion Paul Duveen in a non-title match. In October 1936, [[Boston]] promoter [[Paul Bowser]] brought Casey to the United States.\n\nOn 11 February 1938, he received the biggest victory of his career when he defeated the legendary [[Lou Thesz]] to win the [[AWA World Heavyweight Championship (Boston version)|American Wrestling Association World Heavyweight Championship]]. On 26 August, he wrestled [[Danno O'Mahony]] to a draw after ten five-minute rounds in the [[Professional wrestling in the United Kingdom|European style]]. In September 1938, Casey was stripped of the NWA title, officially for being out of the country. He continued to be recognized as champion by the Boston-based American Wrestling Association. On 18 September, he beat O'Mahony in Munster in a finish match in 18 rounds and 97 minutes.\n\nOn 2 March 1939, Casey lost the [[AWA World Heavyweight Championship (Boston version)|AWA World Championship]] to Marvin Westenberg in Boston. On 29 March, he beat [[Gus Sonnenberg]] to start his second reign as AWA champion, losing the title to [[Ed Don George]] on 18 April in [[Albany, New York]]. He defeated George to win his start his third reign as AWA World Champion on 29 November 1939, dropping the title to [[The French Angel]] on 13 May 1940. In the same year, he beat Richard Codman for the Governor's Cup in [[Cambridge, Massachusetts]]. He defeated the U.S. boxing champion Tiger Warrenton and issued a challenge to [[Joe Louis]] which went unanswered. On 12 November 1941, he challenged [[Earl McCready]] for the [[NWA British Empire Heavyweight Championship (Toronto version)|British Empire Heavyweight Championship]] but the match was fought to no contest.\n\nOn 13 May 1942, Casey beat French Angel for his fourth reign as AWA champion. While still champion, Casey joined the [[United States Army]] during [[World War II]], serving from 1942 to 1944. On 6 June 1945 in Boston, he defeated Frank Sexton to start his sixth reign as AWA champion and re-lost the title to Sexton three weeks later. In 1947, he announced his retirement at age 38. He opened a [[liquor store]] near [[Nantasket Beach]] in [[Hull, Massachusetts]]. He also owned a bar on Massachusetts Ave., Boston in the 1950s.\n\n== Personal life ==\nIn 1983, the Casey family organized a family reunion in Sneem, Ireland. On 10 January 1987, he died at age 78.\n\n== Championships and accomplishments ==\nIn 1982, Casey was awarded the Irish Hall of Fame award by [[1956 Summer Olympics|1956 Olympic Gold Medalist]] [[Ron Delany|Ronnie Delaney]].\n\n===Sport rowing===\n*Tug O' War Munster Championship (1932)\n*All-England Rowing Championship (1936)\n\n===Professional wrestling===\n*'''American Wrestling Association ''(Boston)'''''\n**[[AWA World Heavyweight Championship (Boston version)|AWA World Heavyweight Championship]] (6 times)\n*'''Other titles'''\n**Governor's Cup (1940)\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/profiles/s/steve-casey.html Profile at OWW]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Casey, Steve}}\n[[Category:1909 births]]\n[[Category:1987 deaths]]\n[[Category:Irish male professional wrestlers]]\n[[Category:Irish male rowers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{Infobox professional wrestler\n|name        = Steve Casey\n|names       =Steve Casey\n|image       = Steve 'The Crusher' Casey.jpg\n|caption    = Bronze statue of 'The Crusher' in Sneem\n|height      = {{height|foot=6|inch=4}}\n|weight      = {{convert|238|lb|kg|abbr=on}}\n|birth_date  = 4 December 1908\n|birth_place = [[Sneem]], [[History of Ireland (1801\u20131923)|Ireland]]\n|death_date  = 10 January 1987 (aged 78)\n|death_place =\n|birth_name = Stephen Casey\n|trainer     = Mike Casey\n|debut       = 3 March 1936\n|retired     = 1947\n}}\n\n'''Stephen Casey''' (4 December 1908 \u2013 10 January 1987) was an [[Ireland|Irish]] [[Rowing (sport)|sport rower]] and world champion [[Professional wrestling|professional wrestler]]. He was the second Irish wrestler, after [[Danno O'Mahoney]], to become a world champion.\n\n== Rowing ==\nCasey was the eldest of seven sons of Mike Casey, a bare-knuckle boxer. Steve Casey rowed in the Sneem senior crew with his father and the O'Connor Brothers. The Sneem/Casey Team won the Tug-O-War Munster Championship in 1932. Casey went on to win the Salter Challenge Cup with his brothers during 1930 to 1933. In 1936, he became the All-England Rowing Champion with his brothers Paddy, Tom and Mick. In the same year, the Caseys qualified for [[1936 Summer Olympics|the Olympics]] in [[Rowing at the 1936 Summer Olympics|rowing]] but were disqualified for Steve and Paddy being professional wrestlers because Steve had wrestled two professional matches before the Olympics.\n\n== Professional wrestling ==\nIn 1935, Steve and his brother Paddy Casey joined the British Amateur Wrestling Team. Steve Casey debuted as a professional wrestler on 3 March 1936 by beating the Irish Canadian Heavyweight Champion Paul Duveen in a non-title match. In October 1936, [[Boston]] promoter [[Paul Bowser]] brought Casey to the United States.\n\nOn 11 February 1938, he received the biggest victory of his career when he defeated the legendary [[Lou Thesz]] to win the [[AWA World Heavyweight Championship (Boston version)|American Wrestling Association World Heavyweight Championship]]. On 26 August, he wrestled [[Danno O'Mahony]] to a draw after ten five-minute rounds in the [[Professional wrestling in the United Kingdom|European style]]. In September 1938, Casey was stripped of the NWA title, officially for being out of the country. He continued to be recognized as champion by the Boston-based American Wrestling Association. On 18 September, he beat O'Mahony in Munster in a finish match in 18 rounds and 97 minutes.\n\nOn 2 March 1939, Casey lost the [[AWA World Heavyweight Championship (Boston version)|AWA World Championship]] to Marvin Westenberg in Boston. On 29 March, he beat [[Gus Sonnenberg]] to start his second reign as AWA champion, losing the title to [[Ed Don George]] on 18 April in [[Albany, New York]]. He defeated George to win his start his third reign as AWA World Champion on 29 November 1939, dropping the title to [[The French Angel]] on 13 May 1940. In the same year, he beat Richard Codman for the Governor's Cup in [[Cambridge, Massachusetts]]. He defeated the U.S. boxing champion Tiger Warrenton and issued a challenge to [[Joe Louis]] which went unanswered. On 12 November 1941, he challenged [[Earl McCready]] for the [[NWA British Empire Heavyweight Championship (Toronto version)|British Empire Heavyweight Championship]] but the match was fought to no contest.\n\nOn 13 May 1942, Casey beat French Angel for his fourth reign as AWA champion. While still champion, Casey joined the [[United States Army]] during [[World War II]], serving from 1942 to 1944. On 6 June 1945 in Boston, he defeated Frank Sexton to start his sixth reign as AWA champion and re-lost the title to Sexton three weeks later. In 1947, he announced his retirement at age 38. He opened a [[liquor store]] near [[Nantasket Beach]] in [[Hull, Massachusetts]]. He also owned a bar on Massachusetts Ave., Boston in the 1950s.\n\n== Personal life ==\nIn 1983, the Casey family organized a family reunion in Sneem, Ireland. On 10 January 1987, he died at age 78.\n\n== Championships and accomplishments ==\nIn 1982, Casey was awarded the Irish Hall of Fame award by [[1956 Summer Olympics|1956 Olympic Gold Medalist]] [[Ron Delany|Ronnie Delaney]].\n\n===Sport rowing===\n*Tug O' War Munster Championship (1932)\n*All-England Rowing Championship (1936)\n\n===Professional wrestling===\n*'''American Wrestling Association ''(Boston)'''''\n**[[AWA World Heavyweight Championship (Boston version)|AWA World Heavyweight Championship]] (6 times)\n*'''Other titles'''\n**Governor's Cup (1940)\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/profiles/s/steve-casey.html Profile at OWW]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Casey, Steve}}\n[[Category:1909 births]]\n[[Category:1987 deaths]]\n[[Category:Irish male professional wrestlers]]\n[[Category:Irish male rowers]]\n", "name_user": "Tim O'Sullivan from sneem", "label": "safe", "comment": "more information about Steve's family", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Steve_Casey"}
{"title_page": "FC Rukh Brest", "text_new": "{{Infobox football club\n| clubname      = F\u0421 Rukh Brest\n| fullname      = Football Club Rukh Brest\n| image         = Rukh-Brest.png\n| image_size    = 150px\n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| founded       = 2016\n| dissolved     = \n| ground        = Yunost Stadium, [[Brest, Belarus|Brest]]\n| capacity      = 2,310\n| owner         = \n| chairman      = \n| manager       = [[Aleksandr Sednyov]]\n| league        = [[Belarusian Premier League]]\n| season        = [[2019 Belarusian First League|2019]]\n| position      = [[Belarusian First League]], 3rd (promoted)\n| website       = http://rukh.by\n| pattern_la1   = _zira1819h\n| pattern_b1    = _zira1819h\n| pattern_ra1   = _zira1819h\n| pattern_sh1   = \n| pattern_so1   = \n| leftarm1      = AEE6F5\n| body1         = AEE6F5\n| rightarm1     = AEE6F5\n| shorts1       = 000044\n| socks1        = AEE6F5\n| pattern_la2   = _jomagalaxy1819n\n| pattern_b2    = _jomagalaxy1819n\n| pattern_ra2   = _jomagalaxy1819n\n| pattern_sh2   = \n| pattern_so2   = \n| leftarm2      = 000044\n| body2         = 000044\n| rightarm2     = 000044\n| shorts2       = AEE6F5\n| socks2        = 000044\n}}\n\n'''FC Rukh Brest''' is a [[association football|football]] team from [[Brest, Belarus|Brest]], [[Belarus]], currently playing in the [[Belarusian Premier League]].\n\n==History==\nThe club was founded in 2016 as an amateur team. In 2018, they re-established themselves as a [[farm club]] of [[FC Dinamo Brest|Dinamo Brest]] and joined the [[Belarusian Second League]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dynamo-brest.by/novosti/klub/futbolnyj-klub-rukh-stal-farm-klubom-dinamo-brest|title=\u0424\u0443\u0442\u0431\u043e\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u043a\u043b\u0443\u0431 \u0420\u0443\u0445 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u043b \u0444\u0430\u0440\u043c-\u043a\u043b\u0443\u0431\u043e\u043c \u0414\u0438\u043d\u0430\u043c\u043e-\u0411\u0440\u0435\u0441\u0442|date=2 November 2017|accessdate=4 January 2019}}</ref> They won the Second League in their debut season, and made their [[Belarusian First League]] debut in 2019. Before the start of the season, they ended their partnership with Dinamo Brest and became an independent club.\n\n==Current squad==\n''As of April 2020''\n\n{{Fs start}}\n{{Fs player|no=1|name=[[Alyaksandr Nyachayew]]|nat=BLR|pos=GK}}\n{{Fs player|no=3|name=[[Artsyom Rakhmanaw]]|nat=BLR|pos=DF}}\n{{Fs player|no=4|name=[[Andrey Pilipovets]]|nat=BLR|pos=DF}}\n{{Fs player|no=5|name=[[Jo\u00e3o William]]|nat=BRA|pos=DF}}\n{{Fs player|no=7|name=[[Oleg Nikiforenko]]|nat=BLR|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs player|no=8|name=[[Chidi Osuchukwu]]|nat=NGA|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs player|no=10|name=[[Pavel Sedko]]|nat=BLR|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs player|no=11|name=[[Aleksey Antilevskiy]]|nat=BLR|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs player|no=13|name=[[Oleksandr Mihunov]]|nat=UKR|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs player|no=14|name=[[Vladislav Vasiliev]]|nat=KAZ|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs player|no=15|name=[[Yegor Bogomolskiy]]|nat=BLR|pos=FW}}\n{{Fs player|no=16|name=[[Raman Stsyapanaw]]|nat=BLR|pos=GK}}\n{{Fs player|no=17|name=[[Vladislav Morozov]]|nat=BLR|pos=FW}}\n{{Fs player|no=19|name=[[Denis Grechikho]]|nat=BLR|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs mid}}\n{{Fs player|no=20|name=[[Artem Kontsevoy (footballer, born 1999)|Artem Kontsevoy]]|nat=BLR|pos=FW}}\n{{Fs player|no=22|name=[[Gheorghe Andronic]]|nat=MDA|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs player|no=24|name=[[Vital Hayduchyk]]|nat=BLR|pos=DF}}\n{{Fs player|no=26|name=[[Sergey Tikhonovsky]]|nat=BLR|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs player|no=27|name=[[Igor Shumilov]]|nat=BLR|pos=DF}}\n{{Fs player|no=29|name=[[Yaroslav Oreshkevich]]|nat=BLR|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs player|no=31|name=[[Maksim Chizh]]|nat=BLR|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs player|no=34|name=[[Artsyom Pyatrenka]]|nat=BLR|pos=FW}}\n{{Fs player|no=35|name=[[Artem Denisenko]]|nat=BLR|pos=GK}}\n{{Fs player|no=50|name=[[Oleksiy Kovtun]]|nat=UKR|pos=DF}}\n{{Fs player|no=59|name=[[Illya Kalpachuk]]|nat=BLR|pos=DF}}\n{{Fs player|no=77|name=[[Abdoulaye Diallo (footballer, born 1996)|Abdoulaye Diallo]]|nat=SEN|pos=FW}}\n{{Fs player|no=