{"title_page": "Unai Sim\u00f3n", "text_new": "{{short description|Spanish footballer}}\n{{Spanish name|Sim\u00f3n|Mendibil}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Unai Sim\u00f3n\n| image = Unai Sim\u00f3n Mendibil.jpg\n| caption = Sim\u00f3n with [[Spain national under-18 football team|Spain U18s]] in 2015\n| fullname = Unai Sim\u00f3n Mendibil\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1997|6|11|df=y}} \n| birth_place = [[Vitoria-Gasteiz|Vitoria]], Spain\n| height = 1.92 m\n| position = [[Goalkeeper (association football)|Goalkeeper]]\n| currentclub = [[Athletic Bilbao]]\n| clubnumber = 1\n| youthyears1 = | youthclubs1 = [[CD Aurrer\u00e1 de Vitoria|Aurrer\u00e1 Vitoria]]\n| youthyears2 = 2011\u20132014 | youthclubs2 = [[Athletic Bilbao cantera|Athletic Bilbao]]\n| years1 = 2014\u20132016 | clubs1 = [[CD Basconia|Basconia]] | caps1 = 36 | goals1 = 0\n| years2 = 2016\u20132018 | clubs2 = [[Bilbao Athletic]] | caps2 = 58 | goals2 = 0\n| years3 = 2018\u2013 | clubs3 = [[Athletic Bilbao]] | caps3 = 31 | goals3 = 0\n| nationalyears1 = 2013 | nationalteam1 = [[Spain national under-16 football team|Spain U16]] | nationalcaps1 = 1 | nationalgoals1 = 0\n| nationalyears2 = 2015 | nationalteam2 = [[Spain national under-18 football team|Spain U18]] | nationalcaps2 = 3 | nationalgoals2 = 0\n| nationalyears3 = 2015\u20132016 | nationalteam3 = [[Spain national under-19 football team|Spain U19]] | nationalcaps3 = 4 | nationalgoals3 = 0\n| nationalyears4 = 2017\u20132019 | nationalteam4 = [[Spain national under-21 football team|Spain U21]] | nationalcaps4 = 10 | nationalgoals4 = 0\n| club-update = 16 March 2020 (UTC)\n| nationalteam-update = 16 June 2019\n}}\n'''Unai Sim\u00f3n Mendibil''' ({{IPA-eu|unai s\u033aimon|lang}}; {{IPA-es|u\u02c8naj si\u02c8mon|lang}};born 11 June 1997) is a Spanish professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]] for [[Athletic Bilbao]].\n\n==Club career==\nSim\u00f3n was born in [[Vitoria-Gasteiz]], [[\u00c1lava]], [[Basque Country (autonomous community)|Basque Country]], and joined [[Athletic Bilbao]]'s youth system in 2011, from [[CD Aurrer\u00e1 de Vitoria]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lacanteradelezama.com/entrevista-a-unai-simon/|title=Entrevista a Unai Simon|trans-title=Interview to Unai Simon|publisher=La Cantera de Lezama|language=es|date=11 July 2015|accessdate=18 July 2017}}</ref> He made his debut as a senior with [[CD Basconia|the farm team]] in the [[2014\u201315 Tercera Divisi\u00f3n|2014\u201315 season]], in [[Tercera Divisi\u00f3n]].\n\nOn 8 June 2016, Sim\u00f3n was promoted to [[Bilbao Athletic|the reserves]], [[2015\u201316 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|freshly relegated]] to [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.athletic-club.eus/en/news/16822/leaving-basconia.html|title=Leaving Basconia|publisher=Athletic Bilbao|date=8 June 2016|accessdate=18 July 2017}}</ref> He immediately became a starter for the side, contributing with 29 appearances during [[2016\u201317 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|the campaign]].\n\nOn 2 June 2017, Sim\u00f3n was called up to the main squad for the pre-season by new first team manager [[Jos\u00e9 \u00c1ngel Ziganda]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.athletic-club.eus/en/news/17960/preseason-with-the-premier-team.html|title=Preseason with the premier team|publisher=Athletic Bilbao|date=2 June 2017|accessdate=18 July 2017}}</ref> but continued to appear exclusively for the Bs. On 13 July 2018, he signed a contract extension until 2023,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.athletic-club.eus/en/news/19190/renewal-of-unai-simon.html|title=Renewal of Unai Sim\u00f3n|publisher=Athletic Bilbao|date=13 July 2018|access-date=20 August 2018}}</ref> and was loaned to [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n]] side [[Elche CF]] two weeks later.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.athletic-club.eus/en/news/19230/unai-simon-on-loan-to-elche-cf.html|title=Unai Sim\u00f3n on-loan to Elche CF|publisher=Athletic Bilbao|date=27 July 2018|access-date=20 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 August 2018, after [[Kepa Arrizabalaga]]'s departure from the club and [[Iago Herrer\u00edn]]'s injury, Sim\u00f3n was recalled by Athletic.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.athletic-club.eus/en/news/19288/recovery-of-unai-simon.html|title=Recovery of Unai Sim\u00f3n|publisher=Athletic Bilbao|date=15 August 2018|access-date=20 August 2018}}</ref> He initially appeared to be behind the older [[\u00c1lex Remiro]] in the queue for selection,<ref name=Kepa>{{cite news|url=https://athletic.elcorreo.com/salida-kepa-facilitara-20180808223557-nt.html|title=La salida de Kepa facilita la continuidad de Remiro|trans-title=Kepa's departure makes it easier for Remiro to continue|newspaper=[[El Correo]]|first=Javier|last=Ortiz de Lazcano|language=es|date=8 August 2018|accessdate=11 February 2019}}</ref> but made his professional \u2013 and [[La Liga]] \u2013 debut five days later, starting in a 2\u20131 home win against [[CD Legan\u00e9s]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mundodeportivo.com/futbol/athletic-bilbao/20180821/451393160369/athletic-unai-simon-remiro-porteria-san-mames.html|title=Sim\u00f3n debuta con un parad\u00f3n providencial|trans-title=Sim\u00f3n debuts with a providential save|publisher=[[Mundo Deportivo]]|language=es|last1=Zubieta|first1=Jon|date=21 August 2018|accessdate=21 August 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.marca.com/en/football/spanish-football/2018/08/21/5b7b3ce422601d0f4f8b4646.html|title=Muniain gives Berizzo his first win as Athletic Club coach|publisher=[[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]]|last1=Garc\u00eda|first1=\u00d3scar|date=21 August 2018|accessdate=21 August 2018}}</ref> In just his third league appearance for Athletic Bilbao, Sim\u00f3n played in a 1\u20131 draw with [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]] where he made several key saves and was named player of the match.<ref>{{cite web|title=Isco goal salvages point for Real Madrid away to Athletic Bilbao|url=https://www.eurosport.com/football/liga/2018-2019/isco-goal-salvages-point-for-real-madrid-away-to-athletic-bilbao_sto6932432/story.shtml|date=15 September 2018|accessdate=19 September 2018|first=Graham|last=Ruthven|publisher=[[Eurosport]]}}</ref> However, when Herrer\u00edn regained full fitness in October 2018 he was made the starting goalkeeper, with Sim\u00f3n's only appearances over the subsequent four months coming in the [[Copa del Rey]].\n\nFor the [[2019\u201320 Athletic Bilbao season|2019\u201320 season]], Sim\u00f3n was given the #1 squad number and began the campaign as first choice, keeping a clean sheet in an opening day win over [[FC Barcelona]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/49371762|title=Athletic Bilbao 1\u20130 Barcelona|publisher=BBC Sport|date=17 August 2019|accessdate=26 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n===International===\nSim\u00f3n has been selected for the Spanish under-19 and under 21. July 2015, he was a member of the Spanish Under-19 UEFA Euro Cup, though was the backup goalkeeper to Antonio Sivera during the tournment.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bidebietairratia.com/noticias/basauri/2015/07/22/el-portero-del-basconia-unai-simon-gana-el-europeo-sub-19-con-espana/|title=El portero del Basconia Unai Sim\u00f3n gana el Europeo sub\u201919 con Espa\u00f1a|last=Villapun|first=Jon|date=2015-07-22|website=Bidebieta|language=es|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 September 2017, Simon debuted with the Spanish Under-21 team against Italy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.marca.com/futbol/seleccion/2017/09/01/59a9b49546163fb7378b4583.html|title=Selecci\u00f3n de Espa\u00f1a: Espa\u00f1a da un repaso a Italia|date=2017-09-01|website=Marca.com|language=es|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> 30 of June 2019 he was a member of the Under-21 UEFA Cup, only playing the first game of the group stage, where he had a controversial play before the selection.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.marca.com/futbol/europeo-sub-21/cronica/2019/06/30/5d18fcec268e3ea1378b457e.html|title=La Quinta de Oro|date=2019-06-30|website=Marca.com|language=es|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> \n\n'''Spain U21'''\n*[[UEFA European Under-21 Championship]]: [[2019 UEFA European Under-21 Championship|2019]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48812993|title=Spain U21 2\u20131 Germany U21|date=30 June 2019|accessdate=1 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Athletic Bilbao profile|2136|unai}}\n*{{BDFutbol|22117}}\n*{{Soccerway|unai-simon-mendibil/372587}}\n\n{{Athletic Bilbao squad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Simon, Unai}}\n[[Category:1997 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Vitoria-Gasteiz]]\n[[Category:Spanish footballers]]\n[[Category:Basque footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football goalkeepers]]\n[[Category:La Liga players]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B players]]\n[[Category:Tercera Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:CD Basconia footballers]]\n[[Category:Bilbao Athletic footballers]]\n[[Category:Athletic Bilbao footballers]]\n[[Category:Elche CF players]]\n[[Category:Spain youth international footballers]]\n[[Category:Spain under-21 international footballers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Spanish footballer}}\n{{Spanish name|Sim\u00f3n|Mendibil}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Unai Sim\u00f3n\n| image = Unai Sim\u00f3n Mendibil.jpg\n| caption = Sim\u00f3n with [[Spain national under-18 football team|Spain U18s]] in 2015\n| fullname = Unai Sim\u00f3n Mendibil\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1997|6|11|df=y}} \n| birth_place = [[Vitoria-Gasteiz|Vitoria]], Spain\n| height = 1.92 m\n| position = [[Goalkeeper (association football)|Goalkeeper]]\n| currentclub = [[Athletic Bilbao]]\n| clubnumber = 1\n| youthyears1 = | youthclubs1 = [[CD Aurrer\u00e1 de Vitoria|Aurrer\u00e1 Vitoria]]\n| youthyears2 = 2011\u20132014 | youthclubs2 = [[Athletic Bilbao cantera|Athletic Bilbao]]\n| years1 = 2014\u20132016 | clubs1 = [[CD Basconia|Basconia]] | caps1 = 36 | goals1 = 0\n| years2 = 2016\u20132018 | clubs2 = [[Bilbao Athletic]] | caps2 = 58 | goals2 = 0\n| years3 = 2018\u2013 | clubs3 = [[Athletic Bilbao]] | caps3 = 31 | goals3 = 0\n| nationalyears1 = 2013 | nationalteam1 = [[Spain national under-16 football team|Spain U16]] | nationalcaps1 = 1 | nationalgoals1 = 0\n| nationalyears2 = 2015 | nationalteam2 = [[Spain national under-18 football team|Spain U18]] | nationalcaps2 = 3 | nationalgoals2 = 0\n| nationalyears3 = 2015\u20132016 | nationalteam3 = [[Spain national under-19 football team|Spain U19]] | nationalcaps3 = 4 | nationalgoals3 = 0\n| nationalyears4 = 2017\u20132019 | nationalteam4 = [[Spain national under-21 football team|Spain U21]] | nationalcaps4 = 10 | nationalgoals4 = 0\n| club-update = 16 March 2020 (UTC)\n| nationalteam-update = 16 June 2019\n}}\n'''Unai Sim\u00f3n Mendibil''' ({{IPA-eu|unai s\u033aimon|lang}}; {{IPA-es|u\u02c8nai si\u02c8mon|lang}};born 11 June 1997) is a Spanish professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]] for [[Athletic Bilbao]].\n\n==Club career==\nSim\u00f3n was born in [[Vitoria-Gasteiz]], [[\u00c1lava]], [[Basque Country (autonomous community)|Basque Country]], and joined [[Athletic Bilbao]]'s youth system in 2011, from [[CD Aurrer\u00e1 de Vitoria]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lacanteradelezama.com/entrevista-a-unai-simon/|title=Entrevista a Unai Simon|trans-title=Interview to Unai Simon|publisher=La Cantera de Lezama|language=es|date=11 July 2015|accessdate=18 July 2017}}</ref> He made his debut as a senior with [[CD Basconia|the farm team]] in the [[2014\u201315 Tercera Divisi\u00f3n|2014\u201315 season]], in [[Tercera Divisi\u00f3n]].\n\nOn 8 June 2016, Sim\u00f3n was promoted to [[Bilbao Athletic|the reserves]], [[2015\u201316 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|freshly relegated]] to [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.athletic-club.eus/en/news/16822/leaving-basconia.html|title=Leaving Basconia|publisher=Athletic Bilbao|date=8 June 2016|accessdate=18 July 2017}}</ref> He immediately became a starter for the side, contributing with 29 appearances during [[2016\u201317 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|the campaign]].\n\nOn 2 June 2017, Sim\u00f3n was called up to the main squad for the pre-season by new first team manager [[Jos\u00e9 \u00c1ngel Ziganda]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.athletic-club.eus/en/news/17960/preseason-with-the-premier-team.html|title=Preseason with the premier team|publisher=Athletic Bilbao|date=2 June 2017|accessdate=18 July 2017}}</ref> but continued to appear exclusively for the Bs. On 13 July 2018, he signed a contract extension until 2023,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.athletic-club.eus/en/news/19190/renewal-of-unai-simon.html|title=Renewal of Unai Sim\u00f3n|publisher=Athletic Bilbao|date=13 July 2018|access-date=20 August 2018}}</ref> and was loaned to [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n]] side [[Elche CF]] two weeks later.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.athletic-club.eus/en/news/19230/unai-simon-on-loan-to-elche-cf.html|title=Unai Sim\u00f3n on-loan to Elche CF|publisher=Athletic Bilbao|date=27 July 2018|access-date=20 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 August 2018, after [[Kepa Arrizabalaga]]'s departure from the club and [[Iago Herrer\u00edn]]'s injury, Sim\u00f3n was recalled by Athletic.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.athletic-club.eus/en/news/19288/recovery-of-unai-simon.html|title=Recovery of Unai Sim\u00f3n|publisher=Athletic Bilbao|date=15 August 2018|access-date=20 August 2018}}</ref> He initially appeared to be behind the older [[\u00c1lex Remiro]] in the queue for selection,<ref name=Kepa>{{cite news|url=https://athletic.elcorreo.com/salida-kepa-facilitara-20180808223557-nt.html|title=La salida de Kepa facilita la continuidad de Remiro|trans-title=Kepa's departure makes it easier for Remiro to continue|newspaper=[[El Correo]]|first=Javier|last=Ortiz de Lazcano|language=es|date=8 August 2018|accessdate=11 February 2019}}</ref> but made his professional \u2013 and [[La Liga]] \u2013 debut five days later, starting in a 2\u20131 home win against [[CD Legan\u00e9s]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mundodeportivo.com/futbol/athletic-bilbao/20180821/451393160369/athletic-unai-simon-remiro-porteria-san-mames.html|title=Sim\u00f3n debuta con un parad\u00f3n providencial|trans-title=Sim\u00f3n debuts with a providential save|publisher=[[Mundo Deportivo]]|language=es|last1=Zubieta|first1=Jon|date=21 August 2018|accessdate=21 August 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.marca.com/en/football/spanish-football/2018/08/21/5b7b3ce422601d0f4f8b4646.html|title=Muniain gives Berizzo his first win as Athletic Club coach|publisher=[[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]]|last1=Garc\u00eda|first1=\u00d3scar|date=21 August 2018|accessdate=21 August 2018}}</ref> In just his third league appearance for Athletic Bilbao, Sim\u00f3n played in a 1\u20131 draw with [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]] where he made several key saves and was named player of the match.<ref>{{cite web|title=Isco goal salvages point for Real Madrid away to Athletic Bilbao|url=https://www.eurosport.com/football/liga/2018-2019/isco-goal-salvages-point-for-real-madrid-away-to-athletic-bilbao_sto6932432/story.shtml|date=15 September 2018|accessdate=19 September 2018|first=Graham|last=Ruthven|publisher=[[Eurosport]]}}</ref> However, when Herrer\u00edn regained full fitness in October 2018 he was made the starting goalkeeper, with Sim\u00f3n's only appearances over the subsequent four months coming in the [[Copa del Rey]].\n\nFor the [[2019\u201320 Athletic Bilbao season|2019\u201320 season]], Sim\u00f3n was given the #1 squad number and began the campaign as first choice, keeping a clean sheet in an opening day win over [[FC Barcelona]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/49371762|title=Athletic Bilbao 1\u20130 Barcelona|publisher=BBC Sport|date=17 August 2019|accessdate=26 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n===International===\nSim\u00f3n has been selected for the Spanish under-19 and under 21. July 2015, he was a member of the Spanish Under-19 UEFA Euro Cup, though was the backup goalkeeper to Antonio Sivera during the tournment.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bidebietairratia.com/noticias/basauri/2015/07/22/el-portero-del-basconia-unai-simon-gana-el-europeo-sub-19-con-espana/|title=El portero del Basconia Unai Sim\u00f3n gana el Europeo sub\u201919 con Espa\u00f1a|last=Villapun|first=Jon|date=2015-07-22|website=Bidebieta|language=es|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 September 2017, Simon debuted with the Spanish Under-21 team against Italy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.marca.com/futbol/seleccion/2017/09/01/59a9b49546163fb7378b4583.html|title=Selecci\u00f3n de Espa\u00f1a: Espa\u00f1a da un repaso a Italia|date=2017-09-01|website=Marca.com|language=es|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> 30 of June 2019 he was a member of the Under-21 UEFA Cup, only playing the first game of the group stage, where he had a controversial play before the selection.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.marca.com/futbol/europeo-sub-21/cronica/2019/06/30/5d18fcec268e3ea1378b457e.html|title=La Quinta de Oro|date=2019-06-30|website=Marca.com|language=es|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> \n\n'''Spain U21'''\n*[[UEFA European Under-21 Championship]]: [[2019 UEFA European Under-21 Championship|2019]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48812993|title=Spain U21 2\u20131 Germany U21|date=30 June 2019|accessdate=1 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Athletic Bilbao profile|2136|unai}}\n*{{BDFutbol|22117}}\n*{{Soccerway|unai-simon-mendibil/372587}}\n\n{{Athletic Bilbao squad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Simon, Unai}}\n[[Category:1997 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Vitoria-Gasteiz]]\n[[Category:Spanish footballers]]\n[[Category:Basque footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football goalkeepers]]\n[[Category:La Liga players]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B players]]\n[[Category:Tercera Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:CD Basconia footballers]]\n[[Category:Bilbao Athletic footballers]]\n[[Category:Athletic Bilbao footballers]]\n[[Category:Elche CF players]]\n[[Category:Spain youth international footballers]]\n[[Category:Spain under-21 international footballers]]\n", "name_user": "Nardog", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:fixingSpanish IPAperdiscussion", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unai_Sim%C3%B3n"}
{"title_page": "Dewan Farid Gazi", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Dewan Farid Gazi\n| office = Member of Bangladesh Parliament\n| term_start = \n| term_end = \n| predecessor = \n| successor = \n| birth_date = {{date of birth|1924|3|1|df=y}}\n| birth_place = Devapara, Nabiganj, Habiganj District, Assam, British Raj.\n| death_date = {{date of death and age|2010|11|19|1924|3|1|df=y}}\n| death_place = [[Dhaka]], [[Bangladesh]]\n| father = Dewan Muhammad Hamid Gazi\n| party = [[Awami League]]\n| bodyclass = \n| mainwidth = \n}}'''Dewan Farid Gazi''' ({{lang-bn|\u09a6\u09c7\u0993\u09af\u09bc\u09be\u09a8 \u09ab\u09b0\u09bf\u09a6 \u0997\u09be\u099c\u09c0}}; 1 March 1924\u2013 19 November 2010)<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thedailystar.net/news-detail-162874|title=Farid Gazi passes away|date=2010-11-20|work=The Daily Star|access-date=2017-10-31|language=en}}</ref> was a [[Bangladesh]]i politician born in [[Devpara]], [[Nabiganj Upazila]], [[Sylhet]]. He was elected as Member of [[Jatiyo Sangshad|Parliament]] for the [[Habiganj-1]] (Nabigonj-Bahubal) constituency in 1996, 2001 and 2008, representing the [[Awami League]], of which he was an Advisory Council member. He served as chairman of the Parliamentary Standing Committee on the [[Ministry of Primary and Mass Education]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Dewan Farid Gazi passes away |url=http://www.thefinancialexpress-bd.com/more.php?news_id=117821&date=2010-11-20 |work=The Financial Express (Bangladesh) |date=20 November 2010 |accessdate=27 December 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thedailystar.net/news-detail-45076|title=Gazi quits but consensus still far away in AL|date=2008-07-10|work=The Daily Star|access-date=2017-10-31|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nGazi was born on 1 March 1924 in Devapara, [[Nabiganj Upazila|Nabiganj]], [[Habiganj District]], [[Assam]], [[British Raj]]. He was born into a [[Bengali Muslim]] family. His father, Dewan Muhammad Hamid Gazi was a [[zamindar]] in Dinarpur Pargana and was the 15th descendant of [[Shah Tajuddin|Shah Tajuddin Qurayshia]] - a disciple of [[Shah Jalal]]. He studied in [[Moulvibazar]] Junior Madrasa, Sylhet Aliya Madrasa, and graduated from Sylhet Rasamoy Memorial High School in 1945. He graduated in 1947 from [[Murari Chand College]] and in 1949 from [[Madan Mohan College]]. He joined the Assam Muslim Student Federation as a student. He campaigned against the [[Bangal Khedao]] (Oust Bengalees) movement of the Assamese people which sought to remove Bengali people from [[Assam]]. He helped organized the [[1947 Sylhet referendum|Sylhet referendum]] in 1947. He carried out campaigns in 1950 to stop religious violence in Sylhet.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://en.banglapedia.org/index.php?title=Gazi,_Dewan_Farid|title=Gazi, Dewan Farid|last=Khan|first=Muazzam Hussain|date=|website=en.banglapedia.org|publisher=Banglapedia|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2017-10-31}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nGazi joined the Rasamoy Memorial High School as a teacher and then worked in Sylhet Government High School. He joined Awami League in 1952 and was elected joint secretary of the [[Sylhet district]] Awami League. From 1952 to 1955 he worked in the Bengali Jugabhery weekly and the English Eastern Herald weekly. He was elected Topkhana union parisad chairman and [[Sylhet City|Sylhet municipality]] commissioner. He was involved in the [[Six point movement|six-point program]] of Awami League and was jailed for it in 1967. He campaigned against military dictator General [[Ayub Khan (President of Pakistan)|Ayub Khan]] in 1969. In 1970 he was elected to the [[National Assembly of Pakistan]] from Sylhet as an Awami League candidate.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nGazi was involved in the Awami League lead [[Non-cooperation movement (1971)|Non-Cooperation movement]] in 1971 in Sylhet. In the [[Bangladesh Liberation war]] he was an advisor of Sector 3 and 4 of the [[Mukti Bahini]] on civil affairs. He was elected to [[Jatiya Sangsad|Bangladesh Parliament]] in 1973 from Sylhet. He served in the cabinet of [[Sheikh Mujibur Rahman]] as State Minister of the [[Ministry of Local Government, Rural Development and Co-operatives|Ministry of Local Government and Cooperative]] and afterwards he served as the State Minister of Commerce. He had helped introduced the wage earners scheme policy. After the assassination of Sheikh Mujibur Rahman, he joined the cabinet of [[Khondaker Mostaq Ahmad|Khondakar Mostaq Ahmad]] in 1975. He campaigned for the removal of military dictator [[Hussain Mohammad Ershad]] in 1990. He was elected to parliament from Habiganj-1 in 1996, 2001, and 2008.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Death ==\nGazi died on 19 November 2010 in [[Dhaka]], [[Bangladesh]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gazi, Dewan Fari}}\n[[Category:1924 births]]\n[[Category:2010 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Nabiganj Upazila]]\n[[Category:Bangladesh Awami League politicians]]\n[[Category:8th Jatiya Sangsad members]]\n[[Category:State Ministers of Local Government, Rural Development and Co-operatives]]\n[[Category:State Ministers of Commerce (Bangladesh)]]\n[[Category:1st Jatiya Sangsad members]]\n[[Category:7th Jatiya Sangsad members]]\n[[Category:9th Jatiya Sangsad members]]\n\n\n{{Bangladesh-bio-stub}}\n[[ur:\u062f\u06cc\u0648\u0627\u0646 \u0641\u0631\u06cc\u062f \u063a\u0627\u0632\u06cc]]\n[[fa:\u062f\u06cc\u0648\u0627\u0646 \u0641\u0631\u06cc\u062f \u063a\u0627\u0632\u06cc]]\n[[ar:\u062f\u06cc\u0648\u0627\u0646 \u0641\u0631\u06cc\u062f \u063a\u0627\u0632\u064a]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Dewan Farid Gazi\n| office = Member of Bangladesh Parliament\n| term_start = \n| term_end = \n| predecessor = \n| successor = \n| birth_date = {{date of birth|1924|3|1|df=y}}\n| birth_place = Devapara, Nabiganj, Habiganj District, Assam, British Raj.\n| death_date = {{date of death and age|2010|11|19|1924|3|1|df=y}}\n| death_place = [[Dhaka]], [[Bangladesh]]\n| father = Dewan Muhammad Hamid Gazi\n| party = [[Awami League]]\n| bodyclass = \n| mainwidth = \n}}'''Dewan Farid Gazi''' ({{lang-bn|\u09a6\u09c7\u0993\u09af\u09bc\u09be\u09a8 \u09ab\u09b0\u09bf\u09a6 \u0997\u09be\u099c\u09c0}}; 1 March 1924\u2013 19 November 2010)<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thedailystar.net/news-detail-162874|title=Farid Gazi passes away|date=2010-11-20|work=The Daily Star|access-date=2017-10-31|language=en}}</ref> was a [[Bangladesh]]i politician born in [[Devpara]], [[Nabiganj Upazila]], [[Sylhet]]. He was elected as Member of [[Jatiyo Sangshad|Parliament]] for the [[Habiganj-1]] (Nabigonj-Bahubal) constituency in 1996, 2001 and 2008, representing the [[Awami League]], of which he was an Advisory Council member. He served as chairman of the Parliamentary Standing Committee on the [[Ministry of Primary and Mass Education]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Dewan Farid Gazi passes away |url=http://www.thefinancialexpress-bd.com/more.php?news_id=117821&date=2010-11-20 |work=The Financial Express (Bangladesh) |date=20 November 2010 |accessdate=27 December 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thedailystar.net/news-detail-45076|title=Gazi quits but consensus still far away in AL|date=2008-07-10|work=The Daily Star|access-date=2017-10-31|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nGazi was born on 1 March 1924 in Devapara, [[Nabiganj Upazila|Nabiganj]], [[Habiganj District]], [[Assam]], [[British Raj]]. He was born into a [[Bengali Muslim]] family. His father, Dewan Muhammad Hamid Gazi was a [[zamindar]] in Dinarpur Pargana and was the 15th descendant of Shah Tajuddin Qurayshia - a disciple of [[Shah Jalal]]. He studied in [[Moulvibazar]] Junior Madrasa, Sylhet Aliya Madrasa, and graduated from Sylhet Rasamoy Memorial High School in 1945. He graduated in 1947 from [[Murari Chand College]] and in 1949 from [[Madan Mohan College]]. He joined the Assam Muslim Student Federation as a student. He campaigned against the [[Bangal Khedao]] (Oust Bengalees) movement of the Assamese people which sought to remove Bengali people from [[Assam]]. He helped organized the [[1947 Sylhet referendum|Sylhet referendum]] in 1947. He carried out campaigns in 1950 to stop religious violence in Sylhet.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://en.banglapedia.org/index.php?title=Gazi,_Dewan_Farid|title=Gazi, Dewan Farid|last=Khan|first=Muazzam Hussain|date=|website=en.banglapedia.org|publisher=Banglapedia|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2017-10-31}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nGazi joined the Rasamoy Memorial High School as a teacher and then worked in Sylhet Government High School. He joined Awami League in 1952 and was elected joint secretary of the [[Sylhet district]] Awami League. From 1952 to 1955 he worked in the Bengali Jugabhery weekly and the English Eastern Herald weekly. He was elected Topkhana union parisad chairman and [[Sylhet City|Sylhet municipality]] commissioner. He was involved in the [[Six point movement|six-point program]] of Awami League and was jailed for it in 1967. He campaigned against military dictator General [[Ayub Khan (President of Pakistan)|Ayub Khan]] in 1969. In 1970 he was elected to the [[National Assembly of Pakistan]] from Sylhet as an Awami League candidate.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nGazi was involved in the Awami League lead [[Non-cooperation movement (1971)|Non-Cooperation movement]] in 1971 in Sylhet. In the [[Bangladesh Liberation war]] he was an advisor of Sector 3 and 4 of the [[Mukti Bahini]] on civil affairs. He was elected to [[Jatiya Sangsad|Bangladesh Parliament]] in 1973 from Sylhet. He served in the cabinet of [[Sheikh Mujibur Rahman]] as State Minister of the [[Ministry of Local Government, Rural Development and Co-operatives|Ministry of Local Government and Cooperative]] and afterwards he served as the State Minister of Commerce. He had helped introduced the wage earners scheme policy. After the assassination of Sheikh Mujibur Rahman, he joined the cabinet of [[Khondaker Mostaq Ahmad|Khondakar Mostaq Ahmad]] in 1975. He campaigned for the removal of military dictator [[Hussain Mohammad Ershad]] in 1990. He was elected to parliament from Habiganj-1 in 1996, 2001, and 2008.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Death ==\nGazi died on 19 November 2010 in [[Dhaka]], [[Bangladesh]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gazi, Dewan Fari}}\n[[Category:1924 births]]\n[[Category:2010 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Nabiganj Upazila]]\n[[Category:Bangladesh Awami League politicians]]\n[[Category:8th Jatiya Sangsad members]]\n[[Category:State Ministers of Local Government, Rural Development and Co-operatives]]\n[[Category:State Ministers of Commerce (Bangladesh)]]\n[[Category:1st Jatiya Sangsad members]]\n[[Category:7th Jatiya Sangsad members]]\n[[Category:9th Jatiya Sangsad members]]\n\n\n{{Bangladesh-bio-stub}}\n[[ur:\u062f\u06cc\u0648\u0627\u0646 \u0641\u0631\u06cc\u062f \u063a\u0627\u0632\u06cc]]\n[[fa:\u062f\u06cc\u0648\u0627\u0646 \u0641\u0631\u06cc\u062f \u063a\u0627\u0632\u06cc]]\n[[ar:\u062f\u06cc\u0648\u0627\u0646 \u0641\u0631\u06cc\u062f \u063a\u0627\u0632\u064a]]\n", "name_user": "Alivardi", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEarly life:Added link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dewan_Farid_Gazi"}
{"title_page": "Pau Torres (footballer, born 1997)", "text_new": "{{Distinguish|Pau Torres (footballer, born 1987)}}\n{{Spanish name|Francisco|Torres}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Pau Torres\n| image = \n| full_name = Pau Francisco Torres\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1997|1|16|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Villarreal]], Spain\n| height = 1.91 m\n| position = [[Defender (association football)#Centre-back|Centre back]]\n| currentclub = [[Villarreal CF|Villarreal]]\n| clubnumber = 4\n| youthyears1 = 2002\u20132016 | youthclubs1 = [[Villarreal CF|Villarreal]]\n| years1 = 2016 | clubs1 = [[Villarreal CF C|Villarreal C]] | caps1 = 1 | goals1 = 0\n| years2 = 2016\u20132018 | clubs2 = [[Villarreal CF B|Villarreal B]] | caps2 = 59 | goals2 = 2\n| years3 = 2017\u2013 | clubs3 = [[Villarreal CF|Villarreal]] | caps3 = 26 | goals3 = 1\n| years4 = 2018\u20132019 | clubs4 = \u2192 [[M\u00e1laga CF|M\u00e1laga]] (loan) | caps4 = 38 | goals4 = 1\n| nationalyears1 = 2019 | nationalteam1 = [[Spain national under-21 football team|Spain U21]] | nationalcaps1 = 1 | nationalgoals1 = 0\n| nationalyears2 = 2019\u2013 | nationalteam2 = [[Spain national football team|Spain]] | nationalcaps2 = 1 | nationalgoals2 = 1\n| club-update = 8 March 2020\n| nationalteam-update = 15 November 2019\n}}\n\n'''Pau Francisco Torres''' ({{IPA-va|\u02c8paw \u02c8torez}}, {{IPA-es|\u02c8paw \u02c8tores}}; born 16 January 1997) is a Spanish professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays for [[Villarreal CF]] as a [[Defender (association football)#Centre-back|central defender]].\n\n==Club career==\nBorn in [[Villarreal]], [[Province of Castell\u00f3n]], [[Valencian Community]], Torres played youth football with [[Villarreal CF]]. He made his league debut with [[Villarreal CF B|the reserves]] on 21 August 2016, starting in a 0\u20131 [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B]] away loss against [[UE Cornell\u00e0]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.castelloninformacion.com/filial-villarreal-derrota-gol-descuento-cornella-puerto-ocasiones/|title=El Villarreal B se estren\u00f3 con derrota en Cornell\u00e0 con un solitario gol encajado en el minuto 91 (1\u20130)|trans-title=Villarreal B had losing debut in Cornell\u00e0 with lone goal against in the 91st minute (1\u20130)|publisher=Castell\u00f3n Informaci\u00f3n|language=es|date=21 August 2016|accessdate=18 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nTorres scored his first senior goal on 8 October 2016, the first in a 2\u20132 home draw with [[CF Badalona]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.castelloninformacion.com/filial-villarreal-empate-polemico-goles-anulados-badalona-descuento/|title=Al Villarreal B le anulan dos goles legales ante un Badalona que el empat\u00f3 en el minuto 94 (2\u20132)|trans-title=Villarreal B have two legal goals disallowed against a Badalona who drew in the 94th minute (2\u20132)|publisher=Castell\u00f3n Informaci\u00f3n|language=es|date=9 October 2016|accessdate=18 December 2019}}</ref> His maiden competitive appearance for the first team took place on 20 December, when he came on as a late [[Substitute (association football)|substitute]] for [[V\u00edctor Ruiz (footballer, born 1989)|V\u00edctor Ruiz]] in the 1\u20131 home draw against [[CD Toledo]] in [[2016\u201317 Copa del Rey|the round of 32]] of [[Copa del Rey]];<ref>{{cite news|url=https://as.com/futbol/2016/12/20/copa_del_rey/1482253090_726650.html|title=Pato evita la sorpresa del Toledo y Manolo, la goleada|trans-title=Pato avoids Toledo's surprise and Manolo, a rout|newspaper=[[Diario AS]]|first=Alfredo|last=Matilla|language=es|date=20 December 2016|accessdate=27 October 2017}}</ref> by doing so, he became the first player born in Villarreal to debut for the club in 13 years.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sport.es/es/noticias/laliga/pau-torres-primer-futbolista-nacido-vila-real-que-debuta-13-anos-5707549|title=Pau Torres, primer futbolista nacido en Vila-real que debuta en 13 a\u00f1os|trans-title=Pau Torres, first footballer born in Villarreal who debuts in 13 years|newspaper=[[Sport (Spanish newspaper)|Sport]]|language=es|date=22 December 2016|accessdate=27 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nTorres played his first match in [[La Liga]] on 26 November 2017, replacing fellow youth graduate [[Manu Trigueros]] late into a 2\u20133 home loss to [[Sevilla FC]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rtve.es/deportes/20171126/sevilla-remonta-dos-goles-se-lleva-victoria-villarreal/1638723.shtml|title=El Sevilla remonta dos goles y se lleva la victoria de Villarreal|trans-title=Sevilla come back from two goals and take win from Villarreal|publisher=[[RTVE]]|language=es|date=26 November 2017|accessdate=18 December 2019}}</ref> He made his [[UEFA Europa League]] debut ten days later, starting and finishing the [[2017\u201318 UEFA Europa League|1\u20130 group stage home defeat]] against [[Maccabi Tel Aviv F.C.]] also at the ''[[Estadio de la Cer\u00e1mica]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.lavanguardia.com/deportes/futbol/20171207/433479671309/villarreal-europa-league-maccabi-tel-aviv.html|title=El Villarreal cierra con derrota un partido intrascendente|trans-title=Villarreal complete formality of a match with loss|newspaper=[[La Vanguardia]]|language=es|date=7 December 2017|accessdate=19 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 August 2018, Torres was loaned to [[M\u00e1laga CF]] for one year.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.laopiniondemalaga.es/malagacf/2018/08/08/pau-torres-oferta-malaga-cf/1025522.html|title=Pau Torres: \"La oferta del M\u00e1laga CF era irrechazable\"|trans-title=Pau Torres: \"M\u00e1laga CF's offer could not be refused\"|newspaper=La Opini\u00f3n de M\u00e1laga|first=Manu|last=Puga|language=es|date=8 August 2018|accessdate=9 August 2018}}</ref> He only missed four [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n]] games during his spell as the side reached the [[2019 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n play-offs|promotion play-offs]] and, subsequently, was recalled by his parent club.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.laopiniondemalaga.es/malagacf/2019/06/05/pau-torres-volvera-villarreal/1093421.html|title=Pau Torres volver\u00e1 al Villarreal|trans-title=Pau Torres will return to Villarreal|newspaper=La Opini\u00f3n de M\u00e1laga|language=es|date=5 June 2019|accessdate=3 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nTorres subsequently cemented his place in Villarreal's starting XI, playing every minute in the league.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.lavanguardia.com/deportes/20191007/47853482340/pau-torres-entre-los-once-que-han-disputado-todos-los-minutos-en-liga.html|title=Pau Torres, entre los once que han disputado todos los minutos en Liga|trans-title=Pau Torres, amongst eleven who have played every minute in League|newspaper=La Vanguardia|language=es|date=7 October 2019|accessdate=19 December 2019}}</ref> In October 2019, he was rewarded with a contract extension until 2024,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.villarrealcf.es/noticias/todas-las-noticias/item/25614-el-villarreal-cf-renueva-a-pau-hasta-2024|title=El Villarreal CF renueva a Pau hasta 2024|trans-title=Villarreal CF renew Pau until 2024|publisher=Villarreal CF|language=es|date=2 October 2019|accessdate=3 October 2019}}</ref> and the same month scored his first goal in the [[Spanish football league system|Spanish top level]], opening a 2\u20131 loss at [[CA Osasuna]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.marca.com/en/football/spanish-football/cronica/2019/10/05/5d9904a422601db5518b4578.html|title=Villarreal are the latest to suffer at El Sadar|newspaper=Marca|first=Euan|last=McTear|date=5 October 2019|accessdate=6 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nTorres was given his first call up for the [[Spain national football team|Spanish national team]] by [[Robert Moreno]] on 4 October 2019, for [[UEFA Euro 2020]] [[UEFA Euro 2020 qualifying|qualifiers]] against [[Norway national football team|Norway]] and [[Sweden national football team|Sweden]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.marca.com/en/football/spanish-football/2019/10/04/5d971507e2704e76198b4571.html|title=Reguilon, Pau Torres and Gerard Moreno named in Spain squad for first time|newspaper=Marca|first1=Jos\u00e9 Felix|last1=D\u00edaz|first2=Conor|last2=Clancy|date=4 October 2019|accessdate=6 October 2019}}</ref> He did not debut until 15 November when he scored in a 7\u20130 rout of [[Malta national football team|Malta]] for the already qualified hosts, within a minute of replacing [[Sergio Ramos]]; [[Dani Olmo]] also scored on his first [[Cap (sport)|cap]] in that game, the first time that two Spaniards did so in exactly 30 years.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://en.as.com/en/2019/11/15/football/1573854279_669899.html|title=Dani Olmo and Pau Torres make history in Spain stroll|newspaper=Diario AS|date=15 November 2019|accessdate=16 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n{{updated|6 October 2019}}<ref>{{Soccerway}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|Europe\n!colspan=\"2\"|Other\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Division||Apps||Goals||Apps||Goals||Apps||Goals||Apps||Goals||Apps||Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Villarreal CF B|Villarreal B]]\n|[[2016\u201317 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|2016\u201317]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B]]\n|34||2||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||34||2\n|-\n|[[2017\u201318 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|2017\u201318]]\n|25||0||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||6{{Efn|Appearances in [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B play-offs]]}}||0||31||0\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!59||2||0||0||0||0||6||0||65||2\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"|[[Villarreal CF|Villarreal]]\n|[[2016\u201317 La Liga|2016\u201317]]\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[La Liga]]\n|0||0||1||0||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||1||0\n|-\n|[[2017\u201318 La Liga|2017\u201318]]\n|2||0||3||0||1{{Efn|Appearance in [[UEFA Europa League]]|name=|group=}}||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||6||0\n|-\n|[[2019\u201320 La Liga|2019\u201320]]\n|8||1||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||8||1\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!69||3||4||0||1||0||6||0||15||1\n|-\n|[[M\u00e1laga CF|M\u00e1laga]] (loan)\n|[[2018\u201319 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|2018\u201319]]\n|[[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n]]\n|38||1||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||2{{efn|name=UEL|Appearances in [[La Liga play-offs]]|group=}}||0||40||1\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\"|Career total\n!107||4||4||0||1||0||8||0||123||4\n|}\n{{notelist}}\n\n===International===\n{{updated|match played 15 November 2019}}<ref name=EU>{{cite web|url=https://eu-football.info/_player.php?id=30836|title=Pau Torres|publisher=European Football|accessdate=18 December 2019}}</ref>\n{| class=wikitable style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|+ Appearances and goals by national team and year\n|-\n!National team!!Year!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|[[Spain national football team|Spain]]\n|2019||1||1\n|-\n!colspan=2|Total!!1!!1\n|}\n\n===International goals===\n{{updated|match played 15 November 2019}} (Spain score listed first, score column indicates score after each Torres goal)<ref name=EU/>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! No. !! Date !! Venue !! Opponent !! Score !! Result !! Competition\n|-\n| 1. || 15 November 2019 || [[Estadio Ram\u00f3n de Carranza|Ram\u00f3n de Carranza]], [[C\u00e1diz]], Spain || {{fb|MLT}} || align=center | '''3'''\u20130 || align=center | 7\u20130 || [[UEFA Euro 2020 qualifying Group F|UEFA Euro 2020 qualifying]]\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.villarrealcf.es/en/first-team/squad/player/1530-pau-francisco-torres Villarreal official profile]\n*{{BDFutbol|23355}}\n*{{LaPreferente|210559<!-- /pau-torres -->}}\n*{{NFT player|76186}}\n\n{{Villarreal CF squad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Torres, Pau}}\n[[Category:1997 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Villarreal]]\n[[Category:Spanish footballers]]\n[[Category:Valencian footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:La Liga players]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B players]]\n[[Category:Tercera Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Villarreal CF C players]]\n[[Category:Villarreal CF B players]]\n[[Category:Villarreal CF players]]\n[[Category:M\u00e1laga CF players]]\n[[Category:Spain under-21 international footballers]]\n[[Category:Spain international footballers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Distinguish|Pau Torres (footballer, born 1987)}}\n{{Spanish name|Francisco|Torres}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Pau Torres\n| image = \n| full_name = Pau Francisco Torres\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1997|1|16|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Villarreal]], Spain\n| height = 1.91 m\n| position = [[Defender (association football)#Centre-back|Centre back]]\n| currentclub = [[Villarreal CF|Villarreal]]\n| clubnumber = 4\n| youthyears1 = 2002\u20132016 | youthclubs1 = [[Villarreal CF|Villarreal]]\n| years1 = 2016 | clubs1 = [[Villarreal CF C|Villarreal C]] | caps1 = 1 | goals1 = 0\n| years2 = 2016\u20132018 | clubs2 = [[Villarreal CF B|Villarreal B]] | caps2 = 59 | goals2 = 2\n| years3 = 2017\u2013 | clubs3 = [[Villarreal CF|Villarreal]] | caps3 = 26 | goals3 = 1\n| years4 = 2018\u20132019 | clubs4 = \u2192 [[M\u00e1laga CF|M\u00e1laga]] (loan) | caps4 = 38 | goals4 = 1\n| nationalyears1 = 2019 | nationalteam1 = [[Spain national under-21 football team|Spain U21]] | nationalcaps1 = 1 | nationalgoals1 = 0\n| nationalyears2 = 2019\u2013 | nationalteam2 = [[Spain national football team|Spain]] | nationalcaps2 = 1 | nationalgoals2 = 1\n| club-update = 8 March 2020\n| nationalteam-update = 15 November 2019\n}}\n\n'''Pau Francisco Torres''' ({{IPA-va|\u02c8paw \u02c8torez}}, {{IPA-es|\u02c8pau \u02c8tores}}; born 16 January 1997) is a Spanish professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays for [[Villarreal CF]] as a [[Defender (association football)#Centre-back|central defender]].\n\n==Club career==\nBorn in [[Villarreal]], [[Province of Castell\u00f3n]], [[Valencian Community]], Torres played youth football with [[Villarreal CF]]. He made his league debut with [[Villarreal CF B|the reserves]] on 21 August 2016, starting in a 0\u20131 [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B]] away loss against [[UE Cornell\u00e0]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.castelloninformacion.com/filial-villarreal-derrota-gol-descuento-cornella-puerto-ocasiones/|title=El Villarreal B se estren\u00f3 con derrota en Cornell\u00e0 con un solitario gol encajado en el minuto 91 (1\u20130)|trans-title=Villarreal B had losing debut in Cornell\u00e0 with lone goal against in the 91st minute (1\u20130)|publisher=Castell\u00f3n Informaci\u00f3n|language=es|date=21 August 2016|accessdate=18 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nTorres scored his first senior goal on 8 October 2016, the first in a 2\u20132 home draw with [[CF Badalona]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.castelloninformacion.com/filial-villarreal-empate-polemico-goles-anulados-badalona-descuento/|title=Al Villarreal B le anulan dos goles legales ante un Badalona que el empat\u00f3 en el minuto 94 (2\u20132)|trans-title=Villarreal B have two legal goals disallowed against a Badalona who drew in the 94th minute (2\u20132)|publisher=Castell\u00f3n Informaci\u00f3n|language=es|date=9 October 2016|accessdate=18 December 2019}}</ref> His maiden competitive appearance for the first team took place on 20 December, when he came on as a late [[Substitute (association football)|substitute]] for [[V\u00edctor Ruiz (footballer, born 1989)|V\u00edctor Ruiz]] in the 1\u20131 home draw against [[CD Toledo]] in [[2016\u201317 Copa del Rey|the round of 32]] of [[Copa del Rey]];<ref>{{cite news|url=https://as.com/futbol/2016/12/20/copa_del_rey/1482253090_726650.html|title=Pato evita la sorpresa del Toledo y Manolo, la goleada|trans-title=Pato avoids Toledo's surprise and Manolo, a rout|newspaper=[[Diario AS]]|first=Alfredo|last=Matilla|language=es|date=20 December 2016|accessdate=27 October 2017}}</ref> by doing so, he became the first player born in Villarreal to debut for the club in 13 years.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sport.es/es/noticias/laliga/pau-torres-primer-futbolista-nacido-vila-real-que-debuta-13-anos-5707549|title=Pau Torres, primer futbolista nacido en Vila-real que debuta en 13 a\u00f1os|trans-title=Pau Torres, first footballer born in Villarreal who debuts in 13 years|newspaper=[[Sport (Spanish newspaper)|Sport]]|language=es|date=22 December 2016|accessdate=27 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nTorres played his first match in [[La Liga]] on 26 November 2017, replacing fellow youth graduate [[Manu Trigueros]] late into a 2\u20133 home loss to [[Sevilla FC]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rtve.es/deportes/20171126/sevilla-remonta-dos-goles-se-lleva-victoria-villarreal/1638723.shtml|title=El Sevilla remonta dos goles y se lleva la victoria de Villarreal|trans-title=Sevilla come back from two goals and take win from Villarreal|publisher=[[RTVE]]|language=es|date=26 November 2017|accessdate=18 December 2019}}</ref> He made his [[UEFA Europa League]] debut ten days later, starting and finishing the [[2017\u201318 UEFA Europa League|1\u20130 group stage home defeat]] against [[Maccabi Tel Aviv F.C.]] also at the ''[[Estadio de la Cer\u00e1mica]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.lavanguardia.com/deportes/futbol/20171207/433479671309/villarreal-europa-league-maccabi-tel-aviv.html|title=El Villarreal cierra con derrota un partido intrascendente|trans-title=Villarreal complete formality of a match with loss|newspaper=[[La Vanguardia]]|language=es|date=7 December 2017|accessdate=19 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 August 2018, Torres was loaned to [[M\u00e1laga CF]] for one year.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.laopiniondemalaga.es/malagacf/2018/08/08/pau-torres-oferta-malaga-cf/1025522.html|title=Pau Torres: \"La oferta del M\u00e1laga CF era irrechazable\"|trans-title=Pau Torres: \"M\u00e1laga CF's offer could not be refused\"|newspaper=La Opini\u00f3n de M\u00e1laga|first=Manu|last=Puga|language=es|date=8 August 2018|accessdate=9 August 2018}}</ref> He only missed four [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n]] games during his spell as the side reached the [[2019 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n play-offs|promotion play-offs]] and, subsequently, was recalled by his parent club.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.laopiniondemalaga.es/malagacf/2019/06/05/pau-torres-volvera-villarreal/1093421.html|title=Pau Torres volver\u00e1 al Villarreal|trans-title=Pau Torres will return to Villarreal|newspaper=La Opini\u00f3n de M\u00e1laga|language=es|date=5 June 2019|accessdate=3 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nTorres subsequently cemented his place in Villarreal's starting XI, playing every minute in the league.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.lavanguardia.com/deportes/20191007/47853482340/pau-torres-entre-los-once-que-han-disputado-todos-los-minutos-en-liga.html|title=Pau Torres, entre los once que han disputado todos los minutos en Liga|trans-title=Pau Torres, amongst eleven who have played every minute in League|newspaper=La Vanguardia|language=es|date=7 October 2019|accessdate=19 December 2019}}</ref> In October 2019, he was rewarded with a contract extension until 2024,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.villarrealcf.es/noticias/todas-las-noticias/item/25614-el-villarreal-cf-renueva-a-pau-hasta-2024|title=El Villarreal CF renueva a Pau hasta 2024|trans-title=Villarreal CF renew Pau until 2024|publisher=Villarreal CF|language=es|date=2 October 2019|accessdate=3 October 2019}}</ref> and the same month scored his first goal in the [[Spanish football league system|Spanish top level]], opening a 2\u20131 loss at [[CA Osasuna]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.marca.com/en/football/spanish-football/cronica/2019/10/05/5d9904a422601db5518b4578.html|title=Villarreal are the latest to suffer at El Sadar|newspaper=Marca|first=Euan|last=McTear|date=5 October 2019|accessdate=6 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nTorres was given his first call up for the [[Spain national football team|Spanish national team]] by [[Robert Moreno]] on 4 October 2019, for [[UEFA Euro 2020]] [[UEFA Euro 2020 qualifying|qualifiers]] against [[Norway national football team|Norway]] and [[Sweden national football team|Sweden]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.marca.com/en/football/spanish-football/2019/10/04/5d971507e2704e76198b4571.html|title=Reguilon, Pau Torres and Gerard Moreno named in Spain squad for first time|newspaper=Marca|first1=Jos\u00e9 Felix|last1=D\u00edaz|first2=Conor|last2=Clancy|date=4 October 2019|accessdate=6 October 2019}}</ref> He did not debut until 15 November when he scored in a 7\u20130 rout of [[Malta national football team|Malta]] for the already qualified hosts, within a minute of replacing [[Sergio Ramos]]; [[Dani Olmo]] also scored on his first [[Cap (sport)|cap]] in that game, the first time that two Spaniards did so in exactly 30 years.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://en.as.com/en/2019/11/15/football/1573854279_669899.html|title=Dani Olmo and Pau Torres make history in Spain stroll|newspaper=Diario AS|date=15 November 2019|accessdate=16 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n{{updated|6 October 2019}}<ref>{{Soccerway}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|Europe\n!colspan=\"2\"|Other\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Division||Apps||Goals||Apps||Goals||Apps||Goals||Apps||Goals||Apps||Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Villarreal CF B|Villarreal B]]\n|[[2016\u201317 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|2016\u201317]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B]]\n|34||2||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||34||2\n|-\n|[[2017\u201318 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|2017\u201318]]\n|25||0||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||6{{Efn|Appearances in [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B play-offs]]}}||0||31||0\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!59||2||0||0||0||0||6||0||65||2\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"|[[Villarreal CF|Villarreal]]\n|[[2016\u201317 La Liga|2016\u201317]]\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[La Liga]]\n|0||0||1||0||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||1||0\n|-\n|[[2017\u201318 La Liga|2017\u201318]]\n|2||0||3||0||1{{Efn|Appearance in [[UEFA Europa League]]|n